What's involved in closing a dispute?
</headline>
<post author="pasde2" datetime="2012-02-18T16:35:00" id="p1">
Backstory: I'm the buyer, didn't receive the item I had purchased, an unrelated item arrived (USPS) with a label that was clearly marked from the seller to me. The label, however, had clearly been cut from the wrapping of a different package - the label itself had had a section sliced off, and some of the original package's wrapping paper was still attached to it. The label also had a USPS sticker (on the underside!) saying "Sorry for the damage." The package itself was not damaged.

I contacted the seller and suggested that he might have mislabeled two parcels that were being sent at the same time. It took several attempts to get him to respond, and at that time he accused me of any number of crimes from lying and stealing to scamming and attempting to commit a felony using the USPS, and said he would NOT accept a return since I had obviously substituted the contents of the package, had definitely received the item I ordered and was obviously attempting to extort a second item.

Sigh.

I opened a dispute as there was clearly no chance that I would ever get any civilized communication from the seller. That's in progress but I am investigating the possibility of closing it, and focusing my personal efforts on tracking down the person who was meant to get the parcel that DID arrive at my address. Just call me Sherlock...

Meanwhile, I've been talking to some people who work for the USPS - all of them were of the (informal) opinion that the two packages were mixed up at the sorting center, labels came off or were removed, labels were then stuck back on some parcels but not necessarily the original parcels, and that (a) it happens frequently at large sorting centers, and (b) just for my own information, many USPS staffers are aware of this and do not use their own service for packages - they always use UPS or FedEx instead.

