<post author="kathrynscollectibl.." datetime="2012-02-19T05:26:00" id="p5">
"I am investigating the possibility of closing it, and focusing my personal efforts on tracking down the person who was meant to get the parcel that DID arrive at my address."

Do yourself a favor, don't close the case.

You're just opening a bigger can of worms...

You do not have the tools necessary to find out who the package was supposed to be shipped to, and on the off chance you actually do find out, what makes you think that they'll exchange the packages with you, that is, assuming that they received your item.

Actually, you're assuming a lot...

1. That the other buyer received your item.
2. That the other buyer will believe you.
3. That the other buyer even exists.
4. That the other buyer isn't interested in keeping what they received.
5. That the other buyer will pay the postage to exchange the package.
6. That the other buyer wiil actually forgo opening a SNAD complaint, instead opting to believe a total stranger who has nothing to do with their transaction.

If you filed an Item not received dispute, call either Paypal or Ebay and see about changing it to a significantly not as described (SNAD) complaint. If you originally opened a SNAD complaint, you opened the correct one.

It doesn't matter if you believe the seller is telling the truth or not, you did not receive the item you purchased, and the seller is the one who is responsible for that.

“As a general rule, if you want to get at the truth — hear both sides and believe neither.” Josh Billings
</post>
