<post author="twillobee" datetime="2012-02-23T15:30:00" id="p1">
I just received a notice that one of my buyer's items came broke. This was the first item I sent by regular USPS vs Priority Mail. Luckily, due to cost and type of item, I had it insured. He said it was packaged poorly. I don't feel it was as each item was individually wrapped with packing peanuts stuffing the rest. There was zero movement and it was in a heavy shipping box. I'm also a stained glass artist and package and sell glass items all over the world and never had anything get broke. I know things happen is why I get the items insured. I have no issue giving a full refund, just want to know when and how to show the order cancelled due to item damaged in shipping.

Do I require the item back or at least pictures? I filed the claim with the post office online and they will have him bring it to his local post office to inspect. Do I require the item back? Between selling on Etsy for a couple of years and Ebay, I've never had an item get broke and not quite sure how to handle it as nicely as possible to avoid any bad feedback. I responded to his message immediately and I'm upset this item got broke to start with due to the care in the packing.
</post>
<post author="garmentvarmint" datetime="2012-02-24T16:52:00" id="p2">
TWILL

"...and they will have him bring it in....." <img src="http://forums.ebay.com/images/emoticons/shocked.gif" alt=":O"/>

The bad news is that neither you nor the PO can force the buyer to cooperate in this Claim! <img src="http://forums.ebay.com/images/emoticons/cry.gif" alt=":_|"/> Ebay does not require buyers to do this.

I HOPE that he will agree to bring item plus all packaging in to the PO for you. And I hope that the PO will take responsibility for this damage. (frequently, they do not. And they blame poor packaging for the problem---and refuse to pay out.)

Now---let's say buyer refuses. You can then ASK buyer to send you a picture, showing the damage. If the pcture is a good one--and you find it believable--then you can send him a refund without a return, without feeling you have been scammed.

But---if there is a strong doubt in your mind---then YOU CAN require the buyer to return the item to you, before you refund. However, keep in mind that he can file a Dispute against you that will go on your Record as a Black Mark. And he can leave you really bad Feedback

Ok---back to Insurance. If buyer does agree to take item to his PO---then you should refund him in full--right away. And you should be the one to wait for the PO payout---if there is one.
</post>
<post author="garmentvarmint" datetime="2012-02-24T17:09:00" id="p3">
i see that you sell both low cost and high cost items. I HOPE this was one of your lower-cost items. Because there is always a high probabity that the buyer won't cooperate with the Insurance Claim---and that Ebay will force you to refund. <img src="http://forums.ebay.com/images/emoticons/cry.gif" alt=":_|"/>
</post>
