<post author="rosachs" datetime="2012-02-25T22:38:00" id="p3">
Do you have a stated returns policy in your listings? If not, you should - it would have answered your buyer's question before they asked... even before they purchased. If it was their intent to purchase and then push for a lower price due to some 'flaw', knowing what your return policy was may have sent them looking for another "opportunity". Just as locking the doors on your car will send the casual car thief moving on to the next, possibly unlocked vehicle.

It also helps when it comes to dealing with eBay/PayPal -- having a policy in place means the buyer is creating issues by not following those guidelines you already put in place. Makes it easier for them to say "look - the seller has already stated they will refund you money when you return the item. So just return it already!"

As to dealing with those already pushing -- simply offer a full refund when they return the item in the condition received. Meaning all tags in place, unworn, unwashed, still in shrinkwrap, sealed/undamaged box, etc. No mention of a partial refund anywhere in sight. Period.

And do ALL COMMUNICATIONS VIA EBAY MAIL -- this give eBay an accepted track of the communications. eBay/PayPal do NOT accept outside email, which is likely how the buyer contacted you about the "discount". Because they know eBay won't even look at that message. Only what shows in eBay Mail counts... so keep your conversation there. If they don't want to reply to you that way after you contact them there.... it's pretty much certain they are fishing for free money and know the rules they have to play by to make it work.

Good luck... and better sales!

-Bob.

