<post author="wizard_mithrandir" datetime="2010-09-02T08:00:00" id="p36">
" Sounds like they are selling crap. The best way to learn ebay, is to do ebay....this program has done alot for me......she seems to be very happy with the help that she is receiving for them. Everything you need to know can be found there. " These are all probably true statements though some are more opinion than fact. Each of the posters likely believes in what they are saying. But one could say much the same about almost any seller here... " Sounds like they are selling crap. Don't buy from a crook on eBay. You can get the same stuff at any area yard sale cheaper....or even Goodwill for a fraction of the eBay cost. Don't bid on auctions; sellers are all shilling. " The fact is, however, most eBay sellers are honest, offering something of value for a fair price. They took the time to source it and make it available where the buyer can easily find it, choose it, and have it shipped directly too them. Some shoppers don't have the time, or the desire, to spend their Saturdays traipsing around neighborhoods hoping to find what they are looking for. In a similar way some people are more comfortable with a formal course or with someone to guide them in the learning process. They need to be told what to do (often repeated in different ways) in order to be able to effectively learn and do what others can read and apply easily on their own. Yes, there are scams, and yes, there are over-priced courses and instruction programs. There are also dishonest eBay sellers and over-priced junk being offered here. But, just as there are mostly good sellers offering fairly priced merchandise, there are also good courses that aren't scams. YOU may not need one but others may. What they will pay is determined in pretty much the sane way a seller gets paid for their items listed on eBay; what the market will bear. I'm not sure why but way back when the word wide web was first introduced I found it very easy to learn and apply HTML. I was never good with languages in school but the contcept of HTML, and later PHP, just seemed to fall into place for me. There weren't many sources of information -- the web was brand new and the books hadn't yet been printed. But I found the information, and learned, for free. Not long after that I began to have people ask me to teach them. I've offered courses (both free courses and paid courses!) on a number of related topics and had many hundreds of students over the last 15 years or so tell me how satisfied they were and how they learned easily with my teaching style. I've also been told my courses are a scam because you can get all the information on how to create an eBay template or website for free online. The second part of that is absolutely true. You can get the information for free -- though I've also seen a lot of crap advice being offered as gospel. For some, too, the understanding will come easy. For others, though, they need to be guided though it. They need someone they can go to regularly to ask questions and receive answers that are provided in a way they can understand and without the worry of being rudely attacked or belittled as some are when they ask basic questions. For some, a course (or college ) is the better way to learn. And to suggest that any such a course, without having seen it, is nothing more than a scam is to clearly show why some people can't find the answers they need here even if the information is free. I don't know Power Seller College at all. Lora and I got to be Power Sellers on our own in the same way we do most things -- we researched, read, asked questions, filtered and applied what we learned. It was cheaper in dollars than the courses we saw at the time but it was expensive in time. We had to decide which was better for us. But I've taken courses, too. I've spent a lot of money on them. The biggest scams, in my opinion, are the formal, sanctioned courses at community colleges and universities I've attended, along with the over-priced text books the professors are flogging. But that's the game you play to get the diplomas or degrees. Personally, I'd look at any course, Power Seller College included, and weigh the benefits and costs in light of my own learning style and see if it delivered what I needed and then decide whether or not to take it. I probably wouldn't. I have neither the spare cash nor the desire to ever become a Power Seller again. But some, the OP included, may consider the advice they are getting in this thread and decide such a course is right for them. That's their choice. What they do with the course information will be their choice too. Whatever you choose, good luck!
