<post author="rosachs" datetime="2011-01-07T12:17:00" id="p53">
I want facts and figures not BS. If all you are hearing about a service is "bad press", there are usually only a couple of valid reasons why: - the service actually is bad. - the service is over-hyped and under-delivered, which most people would consider a bad thing. Consider -- Company A is offering training for some online activity, charging a set-up/registration fee along with a monthly fee. The fees are charges auto-magically to your credit card or bank acount. The sign-up process is easy and promises to make the online activity simple, fun, and profitable. So hundreds of people sign up. And find out that the service is really offering just rehashed information that is available online with a little research. They have no 'new' or 'secret' information, just a flashy way of presenting what is considered common knowledge. So a very very high percentage of these new 'members' decide the program is not for them (why do none of these services offer free trial periods or a sample lesson?) and try to cancel their membership. Only to find that the cancellation link is almost impossible to find, requires multiple steps, and may take 'up to six weeks' to complete! Many of these folks find they are still being billed 2, 3-, or 4 months after canceling... and cannot get anyone to answer the phone when the were finally able to dig out a Customer Service number. For every one legit training service, there are probably dozens that are really nothing more than "billing mills" -- they are looking only to generate that monthly billing, and to keep it going as long as possible. There may actually be content that they are delivering for the fee, but just because you can throw together a web page doesn't make you a web designer. Being able to rehash common information doesn't make you a trainer. Before signing up for ANYthing, people need to research the company offering the service. Check with their local BB - if you can't find a business address, that's also a major warning flag. Do a few Google searches and read past the first page -- it's fairly easy these days for companies to create enough web sites to fill up that first page... check a bit deeper and see if the tone of the comments changes. There's a reason most of the regulars on this board, and others, will warn new sellers away from "training services" -- and it's simply because there is so much information available free that there's really no need to pay for it. And think about this... one of the key abilities any seller, online or offline, needs is the ability to perform research. To check out new products, new suppliers, new markets, new venues, new anything. To dig below the surface and determine for themselves what's going to work and what's not worth the time. If you've been spoon-fed everything.... how you gonna learn to do all that research? When I drive into a gas station, I automatically check the price stated on the pump against the price stated on the sign. I check my receipt and watch the register when I shop retail, to make sure 'special offers' are showing up. And these are physical, brick-n-mortar businesses -- guess how much more I research the online businesses I buy from? <img src="http://forums.ebay.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif" alt=":)"/> Just my two cents -- things were different when I started selling on eBay, but that's hardly any reason to discount my experience over time. -Bob.

