My very first thought on this was simple: How much credit do you get for repeat sales from customers who were initially eBay customers? How much credit is given for finding those folks who may not have found you otherwise, and who liked the service and the product enough to come back for more, and to make those additional purchases from what had better be a lower-cost commerce website rather than from eBay with their fees on fees on fees.

It's a pain to track - I know, I've developed in-house systems for multi-national corporations to match leads to future sales for commission hold-back purposes. If the corp generates the lead and hands it off to a distributor, the distributor gives back part of their commission since they did not FIND the lead, only develop it. After a stated period, commissions return to full level, as the distributor is crucial in retaining customers, and repeat orders are the sign that they are doing that.

If you are actively promoting website sales in your eBay shipments, with inserts, coupons, discounts, and whatever -- then your tracking just got easier. Get the company to create a real customer account for each eBay buyer, and then inform that buyer that they can use that account at your website to make future purchases, be they thru the website or via an 800# or mail-order catalog or whatever other venues the company sells in. Get those accounts clearly marked as eBay accounts and tracking is more accurate and much easier.

Good Luck!!

-Bob.

